    summary: 'The closest companion of the Prophet, the first adult male to accept Islam, and the man whose faith never wavered for a single moment across twenty-three years of revelation.',
    story: `Abdullah ibn Uthman ibn Abi Quhafah, known to history as Abu Bakr al-Siddiq, was born in Makkah approximately two years after the Year of the Elephant. He was, before Islam, one of the most respected men in Makkah — a merchant of impeccable integrity, a master of genealogy, and a man whose natural disposition inclined toward what was noble and good. The Prophet Muhammad, upon him be peace and blessings, later said of him: "I have never called anyone to Islam except that he hesitated and deliberated — except Abu Bakr. When I presented Islam to him, he did not hesitate for a moment." (Ibn Hisham, al-Sirah al-Nabawiyyah)

His acceptance of Islam was immediate and total. He did not ask for signs. He did not demand proofs. He knew the Prophet from childhood and knew that the man who had never uttered a falsehood in forty years would not fabricate a message from the Lord of the Worlds. This quality of immediate and unconditional trust in the Prophet's truthfulness is precisely why Allah named him al-Siddiq — the one who affirms truth completely.

The greatest demonstration of his siddiqiyyah (quality of truthfulness and affirmation) came on the night of the Isra and Miraj. When the Quraysh confronted him the following morning and said: "Your companion claims he was taken to Jerusalem last night and returned," expecting Abu Bakr to distance himself, he responded without hesitation: "If he said it, then it is true." (Mustadrak al-Hakim) He did not say "I believe him despite its difficulty." He said: "If he said it, it is true" — treating the statement of the Prophet as self-evidencing.

His contribution to the financial support of early Islam is unparalleled. He spent forty thousand dirhams in freeing Muslim slaves who were being tortured by their masters. Among those he purchased from torment were Bilal ibn Rabah, Amir ibn Fuhayrah, Umm Ubays, Zinnira, al-Nahdiyya and her daughter, and many others whose names history has preserved with honor. His father Abu Quhafah once said to him: "I see you freeing weak slaves — why not free strong men who can defend you?" Abu Bakr replied: "I seek by this only the face of Allah." (Ibn Hisham)

When the Prophet commanded the Hijrah to Madinah, the Companions emigrated in groups. Abu Bakr alone waited. He asked the Prophet for permission to emigrate and the Prophet told him to wait, and Abu Bakr understood that he was being reserved for companionship on a journey of supreme importance. When the command came, they departed together, hiding in the Cave of Thawr for three nights while the Quraysh search parties passed above them. It was in that cave that the Quran recorded his state: "When he said to his companion: Do not grieve — Allah is with us." (Quran 9:40) The companion in that verse is Abu Bakr, and it is the only place in the Quran where a specific Companion other than the Prophet is addressed directly by his relationship to the Prophet.

After the death of the Prophet, it was Abu Bakr who held the community together in its most critical hour. When even Umar ibn al-Khattab was overwhelmed with grief to the point of threatening anyone who said the Prophet had died, Abu Bakr stood before the Muslims and delivered what many scholars consider the most important speech in Islamic history after the Prophetic sermons: "Whoever worshipped Muhammad, let him know that Muhammad has died. Whoever worshipped Allah, let him know that Allah is Ever-Living and never dies." He then recited: "Muhammad is not but a messenger. Messengers have passed before him. If he dies or is killed, will you turn back on your heels?" (Quran 3:144) Umar later said: "By Allah, when I heard Abu Bakr recite that verse, my legs gave way beneath me and I fell to the ground. I knew then that the Prophet had died." (Sahih al-Bukhari 1241)

His caliphate lasted only two years and three months, yet in that period he suppressed the wars of apostasy (Hurub al-Riddah) with a firmness that scholars have called the second preservation of Islam after the Prophetic mission itself, sent the armies that would open Iraq and Syria, and initiated the compilation of the Quran into a single manuscript at the urging of Umar after the deaths of hundreds of Quran memorizers at the Battle of Yamama.

He passed from this world on the twenty-second of Jumada al-Akhirah, 13 AH, at the age of sixty-three — the same age at which the Prophet had died. He was buried beside the Prophet in the blessed chamber. His final words, according to the narrations, were a supplication to Allah and a request that his burial shroud be washed and used, for "the living are more deserving of the new than the dead." (Sahih al-Bukhari)`,
