    summary: 'The man whose acceptance of Islam the Prophet described as a conquest, whose governance established the foundations of Islamic administrative civilization, and whose justice became the standard against which all rulers after him were measured.',
    story: `Umar ibn al-Khattab belonged to the Banu Adi clan of Quraysh. He was physically imposing, intellectually formidable, and socially prominent in pre-Islamic Makkah. He worked as a merchant and served as an ambassador for the Quraysh in their inter-tribal dealings — a role that required sharp judgment, persuasive speech, and a command of the relationships between the Arabian tribes.

Before his acceptance of Islam, Umar was among the most hostile opponents of the new faith. The early Muslims feared him as one fears a storm. He was present at many of the early persecutions and his name was spoken with dread among the weak believers. The Prophet supplicated: "O Allah, strengthen Islam with the one more beloved to You of the two men: Abu Jahl ibn Hisham or Umar ibn al-Khattab." (Sunan al-Tirmidhi 3681 — Hasan Sahih) Allah responded to that supplication with Umar.

The circumstances of his conversion, preserved in detail by Ibn Hisham, Imam Ahmad, and al-Tabarani, are extraordinary. He had set out one day with the explicit intention of killing the Prophet. He encountered a man who informed him that his own sister, Fatimah bint al-Khattab, and her husband Said ibn Zayd had already accepted Islam. He went to their home in a rage. He heard them reciting what we know as the opening verses of Surah Ta-Ha. He struck his sister when she refused to hand him what she was reading. When he saw blood on her face, something in him shifted. He asked to read what they had. She refused until he purified himself. He washed, returned, read the opening verses of Surah Ta-Ha, and the Quran entered his heart: "Indeed I am Allah. There is no god but Me, so worship Me and establish prayer for My remembrance." (Quran 20:14) He went to the Prophet and accepted Islam.

The Prophet said upon hearing of his conversion: "Allahu Akbar!" — and the Companions in the house echoed it so loudly that the mountains of Makkah rang with the sound. The very next day, Umar insisted on making the faith public. He went to Abu Jahl and declared his Islam to his face. He then led the Muslims in the first open prayer around the Kabah. For this reason, the Prophet named him al-Faruq — the one who distinguishes between truth and falsehood — because his conversion and his public declaration of faith marked the first visible distinction between Islam and the power of the Quraysh.

His caliphate (13-23 AH) was the period in which the Islamic state transformed from a regional power into a world civilization. He conquered Iraq, Syria, Egypt, and Persia. He established Bayt al-Mal (the public treasury), the diwan (administrative register of stipends), the Islamic calendar based on the Hijrah, regular night patrols (he himself walked the streets of Madinah at night checking on the welfare of citizens), appointed governors and then held them to account, and created a system of judicial administration that was centuries ahead of the political systems of his contemporaries.

His personal asceticism stands in remarkable contrast to the vast territories under his authority. He wore patched clothing, ate the simplest food, and refused any privilege not available to the poorest Muslim. When he entered Jerusalem after its peaceful surrender and the Patriarch Sophronius came to hand over the keys of the city, Umar was walking while his servant rode — they had been alternating riding the camel for the journey. Sophronius said to his clergy: "This is the description we find of them in our books." (Al-Tabari, Tarikh al-Umam wal-Muluk)

He was assassinated on the twenty-sixth of Dhul Hijjah, 23 AH, stabbed by Abu Lulu al-Majusi while leading the Fajr prayer. He died three days later. His last wish was that his successor be chosen by the six senior Companions he had designated, and that his debts be paid from his personal wealth before any distribution of his estate. He asked his son Abdullah to seek permission from Aisha to be buried beside the Prophet and Abu Bakr. When she granted it, he wept with gratitude. He was sixty years of age. His grave is in the blessed chamber in Madinah, and his legacy is inscribed in the administrative and legal foundations of every Islamic state that came after him.`,
