    summary: 'The man of supreme modesty, immense generosity, and unshakeable loyalty to the Prophet, who standardized the Quranic manuscript and whose martyrdom opened the first great wound in the body of the Muslim community.',
    story: `Uthman ibn Affan ibn Abi al-As was among the earliest to accept Islam, doing so at the invitation of Abu Bakr al-Siddiq, who was his close friend. He was from the Umayyad branch of Quraysh — a clan of considerable prestige and wealth. His acceptance of Islam was, therefore, a matter of personal conviction rather than social necessity, and it cost him immediately. His uncle Hakam ibn Abi al-As bound him and said: "Will you abandon the religion of your forefathers for a new religion? By Allah, I will not release you until you abandon what you have entered." Uthman said: "By Allah, I will never leave it and never abandon it." (Ibn Hisham)

The Prophet married his daughter Ruqayyah to Uthman, and when Ruqayyah died, he married him to his second daughter Umm Kulthum. For this singular honor of having two daughters of the Prophet as wives, he received the title Dhul Nurayn — the possessor of two lights. The Prophet said: "If I had a third daughter, I would have given her to Uthman as well." (Ibn Majah 110 — authenticated by scholars of hadith)

His generosity in the service of Islam was legendary. When the Muslims emigrated to Madinah and found the water supply monopolized by a Jewish man named Ruma who sold water at price, the Prophet said: "Who will purchase the well of Ruma and make it available to all Muslims, and in return will have something better than it in Paradise?" Uthman purchased it for thirty-five thousand dirhams and opened it as a waqf (endowment) for all Muslims. (Sunan al-Nasai 3636 — Sahih) When the army of Tabuk required outfitting and the Prophet called for contributions, Uthman donated three hundred camels with their full equipment, one thousand dinars in gold, and fifty horses. The Prophet turned the dinars over in his hand and said: "Nothing Uthman does after today will harm him." (Sunan al-Tirmidhi 3701)

His caliphate (23-35 AH) produced two achievements of permanent consequence. The first was the standardization of the Quranic manuscript. As Islam spread beyond Arabia and communities began reciting the Quran with local dialectal variations that created confusion and dispute, Uthman convened a committee led by Zayd ibn Thabit to produce authoritative copies based on the original compilation of Abu Bakr. These copies were then distributed to the major cities and all other manuscripts were standardized against them. The Quran that Muslims recite today descends directly from the Uthmanic codex. The second achievement was the continuation and expansion of the conquests that had begun under Umar — adding further territories in Persia, North Africa, and the Caucasus to the Islamic state.

His later years were marked by internal political turmoil that was not entirely of his making. Discontented groups from various provinces gathered in Madinah and eventually surrounded his home and besieged him. He refused, despite the pleas of Companions who offered to defend him, to permit armed resistance that would result in Muslim blood being shed. He said: "I will not be the first to cause bloodshed among this community." He fasted that day and recited the Quran. The rebels broke through and killed him while he was reading the Quran. His blood fell onto the verse: "Allah will suffice you against them, and He is the All-Hearing, the All-Knowing." (Quran 2:137)

He was eighty-two years of age. He was buried in al-Baqi cemetery in Madinah. The Prophet had said about him: "The angels are modest before Uthman, so should I not be modest before one whom the angels are modest before?" (Sahih Muslim 2401)`,
