    summary: 'The cousin and son-in-law of the Prophet, the first child to accept Islam, a scholar of unsurpassed depth, a warrior of legendary courage, and a caliph who governed in the most turbulent period of early Islamic history.',
    story: `Ali ibn Abi Talib ibn Abd al-Muttalib was the son of the Prophet's uncle Abu Talib. He grew up in the household of the Prophet himself, as the Prophet had taken him in as a child to relieve his uncle's financial burden. He therefore lived under the same roof as the Prophet from childhood and was, of all people, the most intimately familiar with his character, his conduct, and his spiritual state.

He was the first child to accept Islam. Abu Bakr was the first adult free man, Khadijah was the first woman, and Zayd ibn Harithah was the first freed slave. Ali was ten years old when Islam was declared, and he accepted without hesitation. He later said: "I accepted Islam before my father's people and before most men, young and old." (Ibn Abd al-Barr, al-Istiab)

On the night of the Hijrah, when the Quraysh planned to assassinate the Prophet by surrounding his home and entering simultaneously so that the blood responsibility would be distributed among the tribes, it was Ali who lay in the Prophet's bed, wrapped in the Prophet's green garment, as the Prophet walked past the conspirators unseen. Ali remained in Makkah for three days after the Hijrah to return the trusts that people had deposited with the Prophet — for even his enemies trusted him with their valuables. This act of remaining behind in danger to fulfill the rights of others tells us everything about Ali's character and about the standard of trustworthiness that Islam demands.

The Prophet married his daughter Fatimah al-Zahra to Ali in the second year of the Hijrah. Their household was one of profound simplicity and spiritual depth. Ali was appointed the standard-bearer (saq\`ib) in numerous battles. At Khaybar, when the Muslims had been unable to conquer the fortress for several days, the Prophet said: "Tomorrow I will give the flag to a man who loves Allah and His Messenger and whom Allah and His Messenger love — through his hands Allah will grant victory." The next day he gave it to Ali. (Sahih al-Bukhari 3009, Sahih Muslim 2406)

His knowledge was extraordinary. The Prophet said: "I am the city of knowledge and Ali is its gate — whoever wishes to enter the city should come through its gate." (Al-Hakim, Mustadrak — a hadith that scholars have debated extensively in terms of its chain but whose general import regarding Ali's knowledge is affirmed by the weight of his scholarly legacy) Umar ibn al-Khattab said: "Were it not for Ali, Umar would have perished" — referring to specific legal questions that Ali resolved for him. (Ibn Abd al-Barr, al-Istiab)

His caliphate (35-40 AH) was marked by civil wars that he did not initiate but found himself at the center of. The Battle of the Camel (36 AH), the Battle of Siffin (37 AH), and the emergence of the Kharijites all occurred during his rule. He governed with justice and insight, and the letters and sermons attributed to him in Nahj al-Balaghah reveal a mind of extraordinary philosophical and spiritual depth. His letter to Malik al-Ashtar, appointed as governor of Egypt, is considered by scholars of Islamic governance as one of the most sophisticated documents on just leadership ever produced.

He was struck by the poisoned sword of Abd al-Rahman ibn Muljam al-Khariji while praying the Fajr prayer in the mosque of Kufa on the nineteenth of Ramadan, 40 AH. He died two days later, on the twenty-first of Ramadan. His last instructions to his sons Hasan and Husayn were: "I counsel you to have taqwa of Allah. Do not seek the world even if it seeks you. Do not grieve over what you are denied of it. Speak the truth. Act for the reward of the Hereafter." He was approximately sixty years of age. He was buried in Najaf, Iraq, where his grave remains to this day.`,
