    summary: 'The most gifted military commander in Islamic history, who never lost a battle in his life, accepted Islam after years of opposing it, and spent his final years grieving that he would die in his bed rather than as a martyr on the battlefield.',
    story: `Khalid ibn al-Walid ibn al-Mughirah was from the Banu Makhzum clan of Quraysh, the clan most associated in pre-Islamic Makkah with military affairs and the command of armies. His father al-Walid ibn al-Mughirah was one of the most powerful men in Makkah. Military genius was, in a sense, Khalid's inheritance.

Before his acceptance of Islam, Khalid was the architect of the only significant military setback the Muslims experienced in the early period. At the Battle of Uhud (3 AH), when the Muslim archers abandoned their position on the mountain in pursuit of what they thought was a retreating Qurayshi army, Khalid led a cavalry charge around the mountain flank that turned the battle and caused the Muslims severe losses. He was, at that moment, fighting on the wrong side of history.

He accepted Islam in 8 AH, two years before the conquest of Makkah, in the company of Amr ibn al-As and Uthman ibn Talha. He came to Madinah and the Prophet stood to receive him with warmth and honor. Khalid said: "O Messenger of Allah, I seek forgiveness for what has passed of my opposition to you." The Prophet replied: "Islam obliterates what came before it." (Musnad Ahmad) He then said: "O Messenger of Allah, pray for me." The Prophet prayed: "O Allah, forgive Khalid ibn al-Walid for every obstruction he placed between himself and the path of Your religion." (Ibn Hajar, al-Isabah)

From that moment until his death, Khalid did not lose a single engagement. He fought at the conquest of Makkah, at the Battle of Hunayn, at the siege of al-Taif, and then commanded the armies of Ridda under Abu Bakr against the apostates, including the pivotal Battle of Yamama against Musaylimah the false prophet. He then commanded the campaigns in Iraq and Syria under both Abu Bakr and Umar.

At the Battle of al-Walaja (633 CE), he executed a double envelopment maneuver against the Persian forces — a tactical movement of extraordinary sophistication that military historians have compared to Hannibal's encirclement at Cannae. At the Battle of Yarmouk (636 CE), commanding against the Byzantine army in one of the largest battles of the seventh century, he coordinated a series of tactical withdrawals and counter-attacks that broke an army several times the size of the Muslim force.

Umar ibn al-Khattab removed him from command during his caliphate, not for any military failure but for concerns about how the soldiers were beginning to attribute victories to Khalid rather than to Allah. Khalid accepted the dismissal with complete submission and continued to fight as a regular soldier under the command of Abu Ubaidah ibn al-Jarrah. This act of submission to authority, from the greatest battlefield commander of his era, is itself one of the most remarkable demonstrations of Islamic character in the early period.

He died in Hims (Emesa) in Syria in 21 AH, on his bed, of natural causes. His final words were a grief-stricken expression of longing for martyrdom: "I have participated in so many battles seeking martyrdom that there is no place on my body the size of a palm that does not have a wound from a sword or an arrow. And yet here I am dying on my bed like an old camel dies. May the eyes of cowards not find sleep." (Ibn Kathir, al-Bidayah wal-Nihayah) He was the sword that Allah had drawn and the sword never lost its edge.`,
